item.title: Argentina's Vice President Kirchner threatened with gun outside her home
item.description: Police in Argentina have arrested a man accused of pointing a gun at Vice President Cristina Fernández de Kirchner at point blank range outside her home in Buenos Aires on Thursday.

item.title: Analysis: Queen Elizabeth signals nothing will stop her from carrying out her royal duties
item.description: We're back, royal readers, and in just a few days' time the new leader of the governing Conservative Party -- and consequently, the country's next prime minister -- will be announced. As you'll recall, the Queen and politics don't usually mix, but she is involved in the transition, so let's break it down.

item.title: A third of Pakistan is underwater amid its worst floods in history. Here's what you need to know
item.description: More than one third of Pakistan is underwater, according to satellite images from the European Space Agency (ESA), as deadly floodwaters threaten to create secondary disasters.

item.title: Myanmar's deposed former leader Aung San Suu Kyi sentenced to jail, hard labor
item.description: Myanmar's deposed former leader Aung San Suu Kyi was found guilty of electoral fraud on Friday and sentenced by a judge to three years in jail with hard labor, according to a source familiar with the proceedings.

item.title: Starbucks names new CEO
item.description: Starbucks has tapped Laxman Narasimhan as its next CEO.

item.title: Strikes sweep Britain as soaring inflation savages living standards
item.description: Workers in the United Kingdom have had enough of falling living standards.

item.title: NFT collapse, inflation 'pain,' and Serena's next play. Welcome to 'Nightcap'
item.description: CNN's Allison Morrow breaks down the Fed chair's blunt warning on inflation. Plus a crypto critic weighs in on the collapse of NFT prices. And USA Today sports columnist Christine Brennan joins 'Nightcap' host Jon Sarlin on what's ahead for Serena Williams. To get the day's business headlines sent directly to your inbox, sign up for the Nightcap newsletter.

item.title: Lukoil chairman dies after falling from a Moscow hospital window
item.description: The chairman of Russian oil and gas giant Lukoil has died after falling out of the window of a hospital in Moscow, according to Russian state media.

item.title: Here's what might drive up the prices on the newest iPhones
item.description: With Apple widely expected to unveil the new iPhone 14 lineup at its upcoming event next Wednesday, a big question mark still surrounds how much, in this economy, the tech giant will charge for its latest-and-greatest smartphones.

item.title: Not only is Lake Powell's water level plummeting because of drought, its total capacity is shrinking, too
item.description: Lake Powell, the second-largest human-made reservoir in the US, has lost nearly 7% of its potential storage capacity since 1963, when Glen Canyon Dam was built, a new report shows.

item.title: These were the best and worst places for air quality in 2021, new report shows
item.description: Air pollution spiked to unhealthy levels around the world in 2021, according to a new report.

item.title: Big-box stores could help slash emissions and save millions by putting solar panels on roofs. Why aren't more of them doing it?
item.description: As the US attempts to wean itself off its heavy reliance on fossil fuels and shift to cleaner energy sources, many experts are eyeing a promising solution: your neighborhood big-box stores and shopping malls.

item.title: Best fashion at the MTV Video Music Awards 2022
item.description: The 2022 MTV Video Music Awards got underway Sunday evening, with stars including Lizzo and Blackpink stepping out onto the red carpet for the big night.

item.title: Miss England finalist becomes first in pageant's history to compete without makeup
item.description: A Miss England finalist has become the first ever beauty queen to compete without wearing any makeup in the pageant's nearly century-long history.

item.title: Nicole Kidman flexes for latest cover shoot
item.description: Oscar-winning actor Nicole Kidman caught the Internet's attention this week with a new shoot for Perfect Magazine.

item.title: 'World's smallest vineyard' makes 29 bottles a year -- and they cost $5,000 each
item.description: Tullio Masoni makes some of the most exclusive wine in the world, but he doesn't want you to drink it.

item.title: These Copenhagen designers are dressing A-list celebrities, but you've probably never heard of them
item.description: In March 2022, celebrity fashion counterculturalist Julia Fox arrived at the Vanity Fair Oscar After-Party dressed in a head-turning black leather gown with a halter-neck-turned-hand wrapped around her neck.

item.title: Germany's railways offered a month of unlimited rides for $9. Here's what happened
item.description: Walking from Brühl's town center to the train station, I passed a UNESCO World Heritage site. The 18th-century Augustusburg Palace -- one of Germany's earliest examples of Rococo architecture -- draws visitors from all over the world. Brühl itself, 11 miles south of Cologne, has a pretty pedestrianized main street, acres of parkland and the Max Ernst Museum -- the artist was born here.

item.title: He bought a movie star's home in France and paid $300,000 to fix the pool
item.description: Finding himself at a loose end on a rainy day in France, triathlete Jeremy arranged to view some properties in the quaint neighborhood he'd been staying in.

item.title: The 'world's coolest' streets for 2022 revealed
item.description: When it comes to fashion, street style has as much cachet as runway style -- in fact, there are dozens of blogs and Instagram accounts dedicated to chronicling the best streetwear looks.

item.title: An epic hike with beautiful beaches at every turn
item.description: Turkey's Lycian Way crosses steep mountains covered in pines, carob and strawberry trees.

item.title: Europe's most beautiful towns
item.description: Paris, Rome, Barcelona... Europe's cities are bucket list destinations, and rightly so. But the continent's small towns are a dream, too, with all the beautiful architecture and much of the culture you'll find in the big hitters, only with fewer crowds to share them with.
